{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "A bacterium or virus slips past your barriers. Nearby cells notice damage or “weird” molecules and fire off chemical flares—like pulling a building’s fire alarm.",
      "title": "An intruder trips the alarm"
    },
    {
      "text": "Those flares widen local blood vessels and make them leaky. Fluid and signals flood the area, turning it red and swollen—like opening extra lanes toward an accident.",
      "title": "Inflammation opens the gates"
    },
    {
      "text": "Neutrophils rush in first, following the chemical scent trail. They grab, engulf, and digest microbes fast—like a cleanup crew shoveling debris off the road.",
      "title": "First responders swarm in"
    },
    {
      "text": "Macrophages arrive and keep eating invaders, but also collect “samples.” They’re like detectives bagging evidence while still wrestling the suspect.",
      "title": "Big eaters collect evidence"
    },
    {
      "text": "Dendritic cells carry those samples to nearby lymph nodes. Picture a courier sprinting to HQ with photos of the intruder so the whole force can ID it.",
      "title": "Couriers race to the lymph node"
    },
    {
      "text": "In the node, helper T cells scan presented samples. When one matches, it flips from idle to activated and starts broadcasting orders—like a dispatcher picking up the right call.",
      "title": "Helper T cells find the match"
    },
    {
      "text": "Activated helper T cells trigger rapid cloning. The few matching cells multiply into a crowd—like copying a key a thousand times so many doors can be opened.",
      "title": "Clones multiply the right fighters"
    },
    {
      "text": "B cells that can bind the invader get “permission” signals from helper T cells. Then they transform into antibody factories, pumping out loads of matching handcuffs.",
      "title": "B cells switch on factories"
    },
    {
      "text": "Antibodies coat the pathogen, making it easier to grab and harder to function. It’s like tagging a thief with bright paint so every guard can spot them instantly.",
      "title": "Tagging makes targets obvious"
    },
    {
      "text": "Complement proteins snap into a chain reaction on tagged surfaces. Some punch holes, others amplify signals—like setting a row of mousetraps that trigger more traps.",
      "title": "Complement cascades and punches"
    },
    {
      "text": "If cells are infected, killer T cells recognize the infected “ID badge” and induce self-destruct. It’s a controlled demolition to stop the virus factory inside.",
      "title": "Killer T cells remove infected cells"
    },
    {
      "text": "As threats drop, “calm down” signals rise. Extra immune cells die off, swelling drains, and tissue repairs—like turning off sirens and reopening the streets.",
      "title": "The response powers down"
    },
    {
      "text": "A few B and T cells become long-term sentries. Next time, they skip the slow search and expand fast—like keeping the intruder’s photo on every checkpoint screen.",
      "title": "Memory locks in the shortcut"
    },
    {
      "text": "If the invader hides well or the signals misfire, the chase stalls or hits the wrong target. That can mean chronic infection, allergies, or autoimmunity—like guards tackling bystanders.",
      "title": "When the system misreads the threat"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "A gene sits zipped in the DNA double helix. Proteins loiter nearby until a “start here” region is exposed—like a bookmark sticking out of a closed book—making the spot easy to grab.",
      "title": "The gene gets “opened” for reading"
    },
    {
      "text": "RNA polymerase lands on the start region and clamps on. Picture a train coupling to tracks: once it locks in place, it’s lined up to read only one DNA strand in one direction.",
      "title": "Polymerase docks and locks position"
    },
    {
      "text": "The polymerase pries the DNA strands apart just ahead of itself, forming a small “bubble.” Like unzipping a jacket a few teeth at a time, it keeps the opening localized.",
      "title": "A transcription bubble forms"
    },
    {
      "text": "Inside the bubble, RNA polymerase reads the template base-by-base and pulls in matching RNA nucleotides. Each correct match snaps in, and the chain is stitched longer—one new link at a time.",
      "title": "Matching RNA pieces snap into place"
    },
    {
      "text": "As each nucleotide is added, the RNA strand peels away from the DNA template behind the enzyme. Meanwhile the DNA zips back up, so the bubble slides forward like a moving window.",
      "title": "RNA peels off, DNA re-zips"
    },
    {
      "text": "The enzyme hits a termination signal—like a finish line banner. That cue destabilizes the machine’s grip, and the newly made RNA transcript is released into the cell.",
      "title": "A stop signal triggers release"
    },
    {
      "text": "Once the RNA is freed, RNA polymerase detaches and the DNA fully re-seals. The system resets, ready for another round if the cell still needs more RNA copies.",
      "title": "Cleanup and reset"
    },
    {
      "text": "If the polymerase binds weakly or the DNA is tightly packed, it may start and stall—like a car spinning its wheels. If a mismatch slips in, the enzyme can backtrack and redo the last step.",
      "title": "Where the flow can jam or rewind"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "You type a URL or click a link. The browser treats it like starting a delivery order: “I need this resource.” It checks whether it already has a fresh copy saved, or if it must go out to the network.",
      "title": "A URL kicks everything off"
    },
    {
      "text": "If the browser needs the network, it looks up the site’s IP address via DNS—like asking a directory for the exact street address. If it’s cached, it uses that; if not, it queries and waits for the answer.",
      "title": "DNS finds the server’s address"
    },
    {
      "text": "Now the browser opens a route to that IP. It negotiates a TCP connection—think of two walkie-talkies agreeing on a channel—so both sides can reliably send and confirm packets in order.",
      "title": "A TCP connection gets established"
    },
    {
      "text": "If the URL is HTTPS, the browser and server perform a TLS handshake. They verify identity and agree on shared encryption keys, like locking a private tunnel before any real message goes through.",
      "title": "TLS locks in a secure tunnel"
    },
    {
      "text": "With the path ready, the browser assembles the HTTP request: a start line, headers, and sometimes a body. Then it pushes that bundle down the connection like a packaged box onto a conveyor belt.",
      "title": "The request gets packaged and sent"
    },
    {
      "text": "Traffic flows through routers, NATs, and maybe a CDN edge. Each hop reads just enough to forward it onward—like a relay race—until the request reaches the server (or the nearest cache that can answer).",
      "title": "Network hops relay it toward the server"
    },
    {
      "text": "A load balancer may grab the request first and route it to a healthy app instance, like a host seating you at an open table. If one server is overloaded, it redirects the flow elsewhere.",
      "title": "Front doors route the request"
    },
    {
      "text": "The web server accepts the connection and passes the request to application code. Middleware layers may parse cookies, validate auth, and log details—like a security checkpoint before entering the building.",
      "title": "Server hands it into the app"
    },
    {
      "text": "The app runs its logic: reading parameters, calling services, and often querying a database. Each dependency is another stop on the assembly line, and failures here can change what response gets built.",
      "title": "App logic does the real work"
    },
    {
      "text": "The server builds an HTTP response: status line, headers, and body. It may compress the body or set caching hints, then streams the bytes back through the same connection like sending the finished package home.",
      "title": "A response is assembled and returned"
    },
    {
      "text": "The browser receives the bytes, validates security, and decides what to do next. If it’s HTML, it starts parsing immediately and discovers more resources (CSS, JS, images), triggering additional requests in parallel.",
      "title": "Browser consumes and renders results"
    },
    {
      "text": "If caching rules allow, the browser stores the response so the next visit can be faster. Connections may be kept alive for reuse, or closed—like keeping the delivery lane open for the next order.",
      "title": "Cache and connection cleanup happen"
    },
    {
      "text": "If DNS fails, TLS can’t verify, the network drops, or the server errors, the flow breaks at that stage. The browser may retry, fall back, or show an error page—pinpointing where the pipeline snapped.",
      "title": "When things break, the lifecycle stalls"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Your program keeps allocating objects, and the heap starts to feel like a crowded closet. The runtime watches memory pressure rise (or hits an allocation limit) and decides, “Time to clean.”",
      "title": "Memory pressure trips the alarm"
    },
    {
      "text": "The collector pauses or cooperates with running threads, so the “floor plan” won’t change mid-cleanup. Think of it like asking everyone to stop moving boxes while you count what’s still in use.",
      "title": "The world slows down (a bit)"
    },
    {
      "text": "GC starts at the roots and “shines a flashlight” through every reference it can follow. Each found object gets marked as reachable, then its references get scanned too—like a domino chain of “still needed.”",
      "title": "Tracing begins from the roots"
    },
    {
      "text": "Whenever an already-marked object is seen again, GC doesn’t re-walk it. That shortcut prevents infinite loops in cyclic graphs—like putting a sticky note on a box: “Counted already.”",
      "title": "Marks prevent re-scanning loops"
    },
    {
      "text": "Any object the flashlight never reaches stays unmarked. Those are the forgotten boxes in the back of the closet: no path from roots means the program can’t get to them anymore.",
      "title": "Unreached objects become garbage"
    },
    {
      "text": "Now GC sweeps through heap space. Marked objects are kept; unmarked ones are reclaimed and their memory goes onto free lists—like tossing junk and freeing shelf space for new items.",
      "title": "Sweep reclaims the unused space"
    },
    {
      "text": "Many runtimes then compact: they slide surviving objects together to remove gaps, and update references to new addresses. Picture pushing books tight on a shelf and changing the catalog to match.",
      "title": "Compaction removes fragmentation"
    },
    {
      "text": "If the heap is generational, most cleanups focus on “young” objects first. New objects get collected frequently; survivors get promoted—like checking the kitchen trash daily but the attic rarely.",
      "title": "Young-first collection speeds things up"
    },
    {
      "text": "To avoid scanning the whole old heap every time, the runtime tracks pointers from old → young with write barriers. It’s like logging when a long-term storage box starts pointing to something in today’s pile.",
      "title": "Write barriers keep tabs on changes"
    },
    {
      "text": "Once reclamation/compaction ends, threads resume and allocations use the newly freed space. If memory is still tight, GC may run again sooner or expand the heap—like doing another pass if the closet’s still packed.",
      "title": "Execution resumes with more breathing room"
    },
    {
      "text": "Pauses can spike if there’s lots of live data to trace or move, or if compaction is heavy. It’s like cleaning takes longer when most items are keepers and must be carefully re-shelved.",
      "title": "What makes GC feel “slow”"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "A luz bate no tilacoide e excita a clorofila no PSII. Pense numa bola de sinuca: um fóton dá o “tapa” inicial e um elétron ganha energia para sair do lugar.",
      "title": "Luz dá o pontapé no PSII"
    },
    {
      "text": "O PSII repõe o elétron perdido arrancando elétrons da água. É como quebrar uma jarra: H2O se separa, sai O2 como “sobras”, e H+ ficam acumulando do lado de dentro.",
      "title": "Água é quebrada para repor elétrons"
    },
    {
      "text": "O elétron energizado vai passando de proteína em proteína numa esteira. A cada troca, ele perde um pouco de energia, e essa energia é usada para puxar prótons para dentro do tilacoide.",
      "title": "Esteira de elétrons bombeia prótons"
    },
    {
      "text": "Com o bombeamento e os H+ da água, o interior do tilacoide vira um “reservatório” de prótons. A diferença de concentração e carga cria uma pressão pronta para escapar.",
      "title": "Gradiente de prótons se empilha"
    },
    {
      "text": "O PSI absorve mais luz e reenergiza o elétron que chega. É como recarregar uma bateria no meio do caminho para que o elétron tenha fôlego para a etapa final.",
      "title": "PSI recarrega o elétron com luz"
    },
    {
      "text": "O elétron segue para uma enzima que passa essa energia ao NADP+. Junto com um H+, ele vira NADPH — como encher um caminhão-tanque com energia química para levar adiante.",
      "title": "NADP+ vira NADPH"
    },
    {
      "text": "Os prótons finalmente “descem” pela ATP sintase, como água passando por uma turbina. O giro mecânico força a ligação: ADP + Pi se encaixam e saem como ATP.",
      "title": "Prótons giram a turbina do ATP"
    },
    {
      "text": "Se a planta precisa mais ATP do que NADPH, o elétron pode fazer um desvio e voltar para a esteira, bombeando mais prótons. É um modo “recirculação” para gerar ATP extra.",
      "title": "Desvio cíclico ajusta o saldo de ATP"
    },
    {
      "text": "No fim, a luz virou duas saídas principais: ATP e NADPH prontos para abastecer outras reações, e O2 liberado como subproduto da quebra da água.",
      "title": "Produtos saem: ATP, NADPH e O2"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Arranca con un precio “tentativo”: el que ves en una etiqueta o el que alguien propone en una negociación. Ese número es como el primer lanzamiento en una subasta: todavía no es “el” precio, es una prueba.",
      "title": "Se lanza un precio inicial"
    },
    {
      "text": "Entran compradores a ese precio. Si muchos intentan comprar y falta producto, se forma fila: señales de escasez. Esa presión empuja a los vendedores a pedir más o a vender más rápido.",
      "title": "Los compradores prueban el precio"
    },
    {
      "text": "Entran vendedores a ese precio. Si llega demasiado producto y pocos compran, se acumula inventario: señales de sobra. Esa carga empuja a los vendedores a bajar el precio o a ofrecer descuentos.",
      "title": "Los vendedores miden el interés"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando hay escasez, el precio tiende a subir como un termostato: el “calor” de la competencia entre compradores eleva las ofertas. Con precio más alto, algunos se retiran y otros vendedores se animan a ofrecer.",
      "title": "La escasez empuja el precio hacia arriba"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando hay excedente, el precio tiende a bajar: para “despejar la bodega”, los vendedores recortan. Con precio más bajo, más compradores entran y algunos vendedores frenan o salen.",
      "title": "El excedente empuja el precio hacia abajo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cada ajuste cambia el comportamiento: subir el precio enfría compras y atrae ventas; bajarlo calienta compras y reduce ventas. Es como una puerta giratoria: cada empujón del precio mueve a ambos lados.",
      "title": "El ajuste reordena decisiones"
    },
    {
      "text": "El intercambio real “vota” con hechos: lo que se vende hoy a cierto precio confirma o desmiente el precio tentativo. Si se vende todo rápido, era bajo; si casi nada se mueve, era alto.",
      "title": "Las transacciones dan la señal final"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cuando ya no hay presión fuerte por subir o bajar, el mercado se estabiliza cerca de un punto: compradores y vendedores dejan de empujar el precio con urgencia. El precio queda como un semáforo en verde: fluye el intercambio.",
      "title": "El precio se ancla cerca del equilibrio"
    },
    {
      "text": "Si cambia algo (ingresos, gustos, costos, clima, reglas), el “termostato” se descalibra y vuelve el movimiento: aparecen nuevas filas o nuevos inventarios, y el precio reinicia su búsqueda.",
      "title": "Un shock reinicia el descubrimiento"
    },
    {
      "text": "Si el precio no puede moverse (controles, contratos rígidos), la presión se descarga por otros canales: colas, mercados paralelos, racionamiento o producto sin vender. El proceso sigue, pero con fricciones.",
      "title": "Cuando el precio no ajusta, aparecen atascos"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "A lone neutron wanders into a chunk of U-235 like a cue ball rolling onto a crowded pool table. If it gets absorbed, the nucleus becomes unstable and starts to wobble toward a split.",
      "title": "A neutron hits the first target"
    },
    {
      "text": "The U-235 nucleus stretches, pinches, and snaps into two smaller nuclei. In that instant, energy bursts out as heat and radiation—like a spring suddenly uncoiling.",
      "title": "The nucleus snaps apart"
    },
    {
      "text": "The split doesn’t just make fragments—it spits out 2–3 fast neutrons. Picture sparks flying off a grinding wheel; each spark can become the next ignition source.",
      "title": "New neutrons shoot out"
    },
    {
      "text": "Those fresh neutrons are usually too fast to be easily caught. In many reactors, they bounce through a moderator and slow down—like a pinball losing speed—making capture by U-235 more likely.",
      "title": "Neutrons slow down in a moderator"
    },
    {
      "text": "Now the neutrons spread through the material. Some get absorbed by U-235 and cause more fissions, some get swallowed by other nuclei, and some leak out of the system entirely.",
      "title": "Neutrons either multiply or disappear"
    },
    {
      "text": "Everything hinges on the multiplication factor: if each generation makes fewer neutrons than it started with, the chain fades; if it makes exactly enough, it cruises steadily; if it makes more, it surges.",
      "title": "A balance check: sub, critical, super"
    },
    {
      "text": "Geometry matters: a big, compact mass traps neutrons like high walls around a courtyard. A small or thin shape lets neutrons escape, so the chain reaction sputters.",
      "title": "Shape decides how many neutrons escape"
    },
    {
      "text": "Control rods act like neutron “sponges.” Slide them in and they soak up extra neutrons, dropping the reaction rate; pull them out and more neutrons stay available to keep fission going.",
      "title": "Control rods throttle the reaction"
    },
    {
      "text": "As power rises, heat changes the odds. Hot fuel/moderator can reduce capture or change moderation, providing feedback that can stabilize power—or, in poor designs, remove braking and invite a runaway.",
      "title": "Heat feeds back into the neutron flow"
    },
    {
      "text": "In a runaway, each round of fissions creates more neutrons than the last, so power grows exponentially—like a microphone too close to a speaker. In a shutdown, absorption and leakage win, and the chain dies down.",
      "title": "Runaway vs shutdown: the final outcome"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Start with a wire loop sitting in a magnetic field. Nothing “happens” yet—charges are spread out evenly. This is the calm before the field pattern through the loop gets disturbed.",
      "title": "Set the loop in a field"
    },
    {
      "text": "Now move the magnet, move the loop, or change the field strength. Watch the field lines through the loop shift like wind changing through a hoop.",
      "title": "Disturb the field pattern"
    },
    {
      "text": "As that pattern shifts, an electric field pops up in the space around it. Think of it like a swirling current in air—not pushing charges from one end, but tugging them all around the ring.",
      "title": "A swirling push appears"
    },
    {
      "text": "Free electrons in the metal feel that swirl and start drifting. The drift isn’t random anymore; it becomes a coordinated “lap” around the loop—current is now flowing.",
      "title": "Charges start to circulate"
    },
    {
      "text": "Speed up the change (move faster, ramp the field quicker) and the swirl gets stronger, so charges drift harder. Slow the change and the push weakens.",
      "title": "Faster change, bigger shove"
    },
    {
      "text": "If you stop changing anything—hold the magnet still and the loop still—the swirl dies away. The charges lose their marching orders and current fades back to zero.",
      "title": "Freeze it, and it shuts off"
    },
    {
      "text": "The moment current flows, it creates its own magnetic field. Like a self-correcting crowd, this new field pushes back against the original change that started everything.",
      "title": "The loop pushes back"
    },
    {
      "text": "That pushback shows up as a real resistance to motion. Try pulling a magnet through a coil: it feels “draggy” because your mechanical work is being converted into electrical energy.",
      "title": "You feel the magnetic drag"
    },
    {
      "text": "Close the loop and current can keep circulating while the change continues. Leave it open and charges pile up just enough to create a voltage, but there’s no complete path to sustain flow.",
      "title": "Closed loop vs open loop"
    },
    {
      "text": "If you reverse the change—flip the magnet or move it the other way—the swirl flips too, so the current reverses direction. The process mirrors itself with opposite flow.",
      "title": "Reverse the change, reverse flow"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "As moléculas do substrato ficam esbarrando na enzima em solução. A maioria bate e vai embora, mas quando chega na orientação certa, a “chave” encaixa e o contato segura tempo suficiente pra algo acontecer.",
      "title": "Colisões viram um encaixe produtivo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Ao se ligar, a enzima “fecha” um pouco em torno do substrato, como uma luva ajustando na mão. Esse ajuste aperta, alinha e coloca grupos químicos no lugar certo para puxar a reação adiante.",
      "title": "A enzima se ajusta e trava a posição"
    },
    {
      "text": "Dentro do sítio ativo, a enzima faz os reagentes se encontrarem do jeito mais eficiente. É como montar uma peça na bancada: menos liberdade, menos bagunça, mais chance de colisão certa virar ligação nova.",
      "title": "Orientação certa acelera o encontro"
    },
    {
      "text": "Cargas no sítio ativo estabilizam regiões carregadas do substrato e do estado de transição. Pense como um “apoio” que segura o momento mais instável da manobra, deixando a subida energética menos íngreme.",
      "title": "Cargas estabilizam o momento crítico"
    },
    {
      "text": "A enzima pode doar ou roubar prótons rapidamente, como um passa-e-repassa de batata quente. Essa troca muda reatividade e facilita quebrar/formar ligações sem exigir tanta energia do ambiente.",
      "title": "Prótons vão e voltam (catálise ácido-base)"
    },
    {
      "text": "Em alguns casos, a enzima forma uma ligação temporária com o substrato, criando um intermediário mais reativo. É como segurar a peça com um grampo: por um instante muda as regras do jogo e a etapa difícil fica fácil.",
      "title": "Um intermediário covalente aparece e some"
    },
    {
      "text": "Se houver cofator/metal, ele age como uma “mão extra”: puxa elétrons, estabiliza cargas ou aproxima água/reativos. Esse reforço direciona o fluxo eletrônico para a ligação certa se romper ou nascer.",
      "title": "Cofatores ajudam a mexer nos elétrons"
    },
    {
      "text": "Com o estado de transição estabilizado, a reação cruza o “morro” e vira produto. Você consegue imaginar como um clique: a geometria muda, ligações se reorganizam e a energia cai para um vale mais estável.",
      "title": "A barreira é vencida e o produto se forma"
    },
    {
      "text": "Os produtos já não encaixam tão bem quanto o substrato. A enzima “relaxa”, o encaixe perde força e os produtos se soltam, como tirar um biscoito do cortador depois de moldado.",
      "title": "Produtos perdem afinidade e saem"
    },
    {
      "text": "Livre de novo, a enzima volta ao formato pronto para outra rodada. É uma linha de montagem: entra substrato, rola a transformação, sai produto—e a máquina repete sem ser consumida.",
      "title": "A enzima reinicia o ciclo"
    },
    {
      "text": "Se o pH muda, a temperatura sobe demais ou um inibidor ocupa o sítio, o ciclo emperra. É como colocar areia na engrenagem: o encaixe falha, o ajuste não acontece e a estabilização do estado de transição desaparece.",
      "title": "Quando algo atrapalha, o fluxo desacelera"
    }
  ]
}

{
  "steps": [
    {
      "text": "Enchufas la fuente de voltaje y creas una “bomba” de electrones: empuja e− hacia un electrodo y los jala desde el otro. Esa diferencia de potencial es el gatillo que obliga a la reacción a moverse cuesta arriba.",
      "title": "La fuente enciende la “bomba”"
    },
    {
      "text": "Los electrodos tocan la solución como dos muelles en una alberca: uno recibe electrones y el otro los entrega. Sin ese contacto, los e− no podrían entrar ni salir del líquido.",
      "title": "Los electrodos hacen de muelles"
    },
    {
      "text": "El electrodo que recibe e− se vuelve una zona “rica” en electrones. Cerca de su superficie, cualquier especie que pueda aceptarlos empieza a competir por ese flujo.",
      "title": "Se acumulan e− en un lado"
    },
    {
      "text": "Como en tráfico, las cargas se mueven para aliviar el desequilibrio: los cationes se deslizan hacia donde sobran e−, y los aniones se van hacia donde faltan. Esa migración cierra el circuito dentro del líquido.",
      "title": "Los iones se reacomodan en la solución"
    },
    {
      "text": "Al tocar el electrodo cargado de e−, algunos cationes “cobran” electrones y cambian de identidad química. Ves el efecto como depósito metálico, burbujas o cambio de color: es la reducción ocurriendo en la superficie.",
      "title": "En el cátodo ocurre la reducción"
    },
    {
