    {
      "text": "The central bank makes a decision: ease, tighten, or hold. That announcement is the starting gun—markets instantly re-price expectations, like drivers braking when a light turns yellow.",
      "title": "The decision drops"
    },
    {
      "text": "If it’s using the policy rate, the central bank nudges the “anchor” rate up or down. Banks feel funding costs shift, like a store seeing its wholesale price change overnight.",
      "title": "The anchor rate moves"
    },
    {
      "text": "With open market operations, the central bank buys or sells bonds. Watch reserves flow into or out of banks—like pumping water into a tank or draining it—changing how easy liquidity feels.",
      "title": "Reserves slosh via bond trades"
    },
    {
      "text": "If reserve requirements change, banks must lock up more or less cash. That instantly changes their “lendable” pile, like a restaurant being told how much food must stay in the pantry.",
      "title": "Rules reshape banks’ capacity"
    },
    {
      "text": "Banks adjust loan and deposit rates to protect margins. Borrowing gets cheaper or pricier, and saving becomes more or less attractive—like changing entry fees and prizes at the same time.",
      "title": "Retail rates re-price"
